**3. SecurityConfig.java (lines 40-44) - Security filter chain configuration:**
```java
.authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
    .requestMatchers("/api/auth/login", "/api/auth/refresh").permitAll()
    .requestMatchers("/api/**").authenticated()
    .anyRequest().denyAll()
)
```

**Issue:** The `denyAll()` at the end (line 43) will block access to ANY non-API endpoint not explicitly allowed. This is overly restrictive and could block health checks, actuator endpoints, or static resources needed by the application. A better approach would be to have explicit allow rules for necessary endpoints or use `.permitAll()` for certain paths like `/actuator/health`.

**4. AsyncConfig.java (lines 12-32) - Thread pool sizing could be undersized:**
```java
@Bean(name = "crawlExecutor")
public Executor crawlExecutor() {
    ThreadPoolTaskExecutor executor = new ThreadPoolTaskExecutor();
    executor.setCorePoolSize(2);
    executor.setMaxPoolSize(5);
    executor.setQueueCapacity(25);
    ...
}

@Bean(name = "gradingExecutor")
public Executor gradingExecutor() {
    ThreadPoolTaskExecutor executor = new ThreadPoolTaskExecutor();
    executor.setCorePoolSize(2);
    executor.setMaxPoolSize(4);
    executor.setQueueCapacity(50);
    ...
}
```

**Issue:** With only 2 core threads and max pool size of 4-5 for crawling, this could be a bottleneck under load. No rejection policy is explicitly defined (defaults to `AbortPolicy`), so tasks will fail if the queue is full. This should be configurable based on expected load.

---

## SUMMARY TABLE

